observations.recommendation:
We recommended that the Municipal Mayor:
a. instruct the Inventory Committee to conduct complete physical count of the entire Municipality’s PPE and correspondingly prepare and submit to the Audit Team the required inventory report thereon;
b. direct the OIC-Municipal Accountant and the OIC-GSO, to conduct the required reconciliation of their records with the inventory report and adjust their records, if necessary, to present the true balance of PPE accounts in the financial Statements;
c. direct the OIC-Municipal Accountant to ensure that PPELCs are properly and completely maintained for all PPE accounts; and henceforth, strictly adhere to the provisions of the above-mentioned regulations to come up with a reliable PPE balance.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor direct the concerned:
a. Municipal Accountant to submit to the Audit Team the lacking supporting documents;
b. Municipal Accountant to strictly comply with the proper and timely liquidation of cash advances;
c. Concerned municipal officials to strictly comply with the proper and timely liquidation of the SAP-ESP from the fund transfer relative to the SAP-ESP from the DSWD; and
d. Concerned municipal officials to provide written justification on the noted deficiencies.

We reiterated our recommendation that the City Mayor direct:

the City Accountant and the City General Services Officer to evaluate the discrepancies between their records and make the necessary adjustments;
the General Services Officer to maintain Property Cards and the City Accountant to update PPE Ledger Cards for each category of asset and to reconcile their records regularly;
the General Services Officer to account for the missing/unaccounted properties and take/recommend the  necessary actions against those accountable therefor.

We reiterated our recommendation that the City Mayor direct:

a.  the City Accountant and the City General Services Officer to correct or improve the existing procedures in managing the City’s physical properties and implement internal control measures to comply with Sections 114, 119-120 and 124 of MNGAS for LGUs, Volume I. This is to ensure that recording and reporting of PPE accounts are reliable. It should also provide adequate measures to safeguard its assets against losses;

b. the City Accountant and the City General Services Officer to thoroughly check, clear and reconcile the noted discrepancy amounting to P82,373,260.78 between the physical inventory report and book balances of PPE accounts for both General and Special Education Funds to ascertain the correctness of PPE account balances in the General Ledger and to establish the existence and propriety of the valuation of the property;

c. the General Services Officer to maintain Property Cards while the City Accountant update the PPE Ledger Cards for each category of asset. Both should see to it that their records are regularly reconciled with the balances of the PPE accounts in the General Ledger;

d. the General Services Officer to account for the missing/unaccounted properties.

We recommended that the City Mayor direct:

the concerned City officials to expedite the immediate processing in the grant of cash advances on a replenishment basis so as not to hamper delivery of public services;

all concerned officers and employees to liquidate their cash advances within the prescribed period or immediately after the purposes have been served;

the City Accountant to monitor and strictly enforce the liquidation of cash advances and/or refund of the excess amount granted within the prescribed period and see to it that no additional cash advance shall be allowed unless the previous ones are settled to prevent the accumulation thereof; 

the City Accountant to enforce withholding of salaries of accountable officers who failed to promptly liquidate their cash advances. Otherwise, institute the appropriate administrative and/or criminal action against accountable officers concerned for their failure to settle their accounts, if warranted.
